The Civil Rights Movement has issued a travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has issued a warning for colored people traveling to Missouri based on discriminatory state principles and racist attacks.
“NAACP’s Travel Recommendation for the State of Missouri, effective August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors and residents of Missouri to pay greater attention when traveling across the state as a result of a series of controversial racially motivated incidents,” the association said in a statement.
The NAACP said it took this step on the basis of current Missouri laws that make it difficult to defend racist-motivated acts before the courts, as well as as a result of the actions of criminal prosecution authorities that disproportionately target minorities.
“Civil rights are being violated.
People are stopped by police just because of the color of their skin, they are attacked or killed," said the president of the NAACP for Missouri, Rod Chapel, to the Kansas City Star.
“We have the largest number of complaints so far.”
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization for the U.S. state.
Among the incidents the organization cited were racially motivated insults directed at black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in disputed circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas while traveling across the country and being detained by police without charge.
The travel recommendation also draws attention to a recent statement by the Missouri State Supreme Prosecutor's Office that black drivers are 75% more likely to be stopped by police.
“The purpose of the travel recommendation is to warn people and warn their families, friends and colleagues of what could happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to be prepared – they should take the money with them for a possible bailout or tell their relatives that they are going to travel through the state.”
According to current figures from the FBI’s hate crime program, there were a hundred hateful behavior cases in Missouri in 2015, bringing the state to 16th place among all states.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that makes it difficult for a company to sue for discrimination in providing accommodation or employment.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) has issued travel recommendations for Texas and Arizona after states approved an immigration law that allows state officials to detain people based on violations of that law, which the ACLU believes should improve racial profiling.
Travel recommendations are usually issued by the Department of State for Foreign Affairs, but recently advocacy groups have resorted to these measures in response to specific laws and trends within the US.
