In her wooden cottage, which is located in the capital of Paniai Enarotali in the Indonesian province of Papua, a woman usually simply throws a sweet potato - in the language of the local "notes" - directly into the fire.
After half an hour, remove the potato and taste it with unwashed hands.
Bardina sits on muddy ground - the cottage is not equipped with furniture - where she also performs her daily tasks, such as washing clothes in cloudy water from a nearby swamp.
A bucket in a room without a roof complements the toilet.
As the youngest of her husband’s four wives, she was not assigned any fields to cultivate.
Polygamy is common here.
Working until late at night poses a danger: most of the men in the village are unemployed and often drink alcohol. In addition, there are soldiers in the village.
“After five o’clock in the afternoon, no one is allowed to wander around the village,” says Bardina.
It is a rare glimpse into everyday life on the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was declared a part of Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum when only 1026 seniors were forced to vote in the form of a public raise of hands before the occupying army.
The current movement of protesters against Dutch rules quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which controlled the entire region with the exception of foreign journalists or civil rights monitors.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua - independent Papua New Guinea occupied the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is such a remote and desolate city that you get to after a 90-minute flight from the capital of Jayapura province to Nabire, and then a five-hour tummy crawling by ride.
There is no public transport at this place.
The city of 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, roofs made of woolen sheets in shades of gray and rust.
Very few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and virtually no foreigners, looked at this place.
Before the arrival of Christians, the locals worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
And that's not all.
“We weren’t used to wearing these dresses,” Bardina says, pointing to her colorful, hand-knit turban, dark shirt and glowing skirt.
"We used to wear only leaves."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of the population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy is one of the worst in all of Asia.
At the same time, however, it is the Indonesian country of gold.
The world’s largest and most lucrative gold mine, Grasberg, which owns Freeport McMoran from U.S. Phoeenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai – a rocky province about the size of New Jersey that is home to about 153,000 residents.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua supports the mining of wood for an estimated $78 billion.
This wealth, however, is a source of suffering for the Papuans and a guarantee of oppression by the powerful Indonesian army.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, Freeport paid local military officials and units about $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including $150,000 per officer.
Papuans calling for self-government threaten this golden goose and are therefore severely oppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969 and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian army.
The mass murders in the tribal area of Papua during the 1970s amounted to genocide, according to the Asian Human Rights Commission.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We Will Lose Everything, a 2016 report by the Brisbane Archdiocese, describes the atrocities that occurred last year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture – according to another report, rape and electric executions are particularly popular – and the brutal suppression of peaceful protesters.
“It’s hard to count the number of casualties because incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The whole situation was aggravated by the fact that Papuan resources attracted settlers to Indonesia.
Of the 3.5 million inhabitants of the province, 83% are converting to Christianity, but demographics are changing with the influx of Muslim immigrants from the Indonesian islands of Java, Bornea, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, or a mixture of vegetables with peanut sauce.
The locals are fighting for survival.
“Immigrants started selling chicken and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans,” explains Abeth You, 24, who was born in Paniai and moved to work in the capital of Jayapura province.
"The natives of Papua - mom-mom (women) - have lost their jobs."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Jokowi, pledged to address injustice and rights violations in his 2014 presidential campaign.
The former carpenter secured his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta in 27 of 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But in Papua, very little has changed and the local people feel betrayed.
“Our heart was broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokpwi in the hope that he would hear our call for justice,” You said.
The fact is that just two months after Jakowi’s inauguration in October, Paniai experienced a great shock.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children sang Christmas songs at a campfire in the city of Enarotali, when two Indonesian soldiers emerged from the darkness of the night on motorcycles.
Two of the surprised children told them they should turn on the lights.
One of the soldiers was touched by the exclamation and tone she was told to, and later returned with four other soldiers, said local parish priest Yavedt Tebai.
Two of the soldiers in the underwater condition chased a group of children and beat them with their arms, victims and witnesses said.
One of the soldiers then fired at a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later someone set fire to a nearby election commission building, and the next day things were still escalating.
About 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered at the football field in front of the local police station and army headquarters to demand justice.
They came with ceremonial hunting bows and performed a waita dance - in which it runs in a circle and mimics the singing of birds - the Papuan tribe Mee Pago.
Several protesters began throwing stones at the buildings.
With increasing tensions, soldiers were given an order over the radio: “If the crowd tries to resist at least three times, you are allowed to shoot,” according to the TIME weekly in an official document, the content of which was never published in the local media.
Jeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Enarotali district of Kego Koto, recognized the imminent danger and urged the residents to flee to their homes.
But no one paid attention to his words.
“When I turned around, someone shot me in the left wrist,” he told TIME on the porch of his manor-painted wooden house.
Kayame does not yet know who the shooter was, but he said the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
"There were a lot of people around and a lot of shooting," he added.
One of the locals, Alfius Youw, said his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, was hit three times.
"I ran to the body to make sure it was really him," Yohanes told TIME in a sour voice, which, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
"I saw that he was dead...I kissed him."
Papua Police Inspector General Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers were only “securing” the station under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” Pudjo Sulistiya, a spokesman for the Papuan police, said in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five protesters were killed and many escaped with injuries.
The report of the murders was leaked to the Jakarta media the next day.
Three weeks later, he delivered a passionate speech to Jokowi in Jayapura, expressing his sympathy for the families of the victims and promising to deal with the violence in Papua.
"I demand an immediate solution to this problem, so that it can never be repeated," he said.
In October 2016, National Security Minister Wiranto announced that he would introduce an out-of-court mechanism to address the violent acts that have occurred in the past.
Almost immediately, however, an apology began to be heard.
“Most acts of violence have taken place a long time ago.
Some of them occurred in the 1990s and some in the early 21st century.
I mean, we're determined to punish these violent acts, but it's not going to be an easy task," he said.
In a June 5 interview with TIME in Jakarta, however, Wiranto said he had no plans to impose any measures in Papua.
Instead, he said that “all cases will be brought before the court.”
Wiranto, who has been accused by the UN of "crimes against humanity" on the basis of more than one thousand deaths during the 1999 independent elections in East Timor, said 11 cases of human rights violations have been settled in Papua, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims of the shooting in Paniai welcomed his allegations with distrust.
“In the last three years, I’ve been questioned four times in total, but I haven’t seen anything so far,” Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
A few years later, he still lives in fear.
"I'm afraid," he says.
"I'm afraid I'm going to be arrested by the army or someone will shoot me."
His brother Yacobus confirmed the view of many residents of Paniai who are afraid to speak about the incident.
According to him, he was beaten by members of the army after he helped bury four of the victims.
"After the body was buried, the army started looking for me," he said.
And the shooting hasn't stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired at villagers in neighboring Deiyai.
The clash, in which one person died and another 17 were injured, occurred between the villagers and the manager of the construction company, who refused to provide assistance in transporting the man unconscious to the hospital.
Ravianus Douw, 24, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company building.
According to police, the villagers were throwing stones at the members and the responses were warning shots.
However, locals claim that a mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) began shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
"There was a panic, we were afraid of retaliation," Domingu Badii, 29, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the arrival of the wounded, told TIME.
“I haven’t left the house in two days.”
The Deiyai parliament demanded the punishment of the police officers involved and the withdrawal of the mobile brigade from the area.
Paniai has always been a thorn in the eye for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development only deepens the separation of the indigenous peoples of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes, who live in the central highlands.
Many of them have joined the Papuai Liberation Movement (OPM), an army of rebels that protects the rights of Papuans by attacking and abducting Indonesian police officers.
Some of the leaders of the OPM come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a result of the attacks, the army has arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of residents of Paniai in recent years, all under the pretext of “securing national sovereignty”.
Some of them will never be seen again.
Paniai is known as a "tragic and forgotten place" among the people of Papua.
