In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands - urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread acts of violence" in Papua, including the shooting in Paniai.
These countries have also supported the OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir shook up the accusations when he told reporters in Jakarta: “In Indonesia, the democratic system is still in place and the media is free, so it is difficult to disguise evidence of human rights violations.”
Local people are calling for the participation of foreign governments.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapurau on May 4, local people were calling for a source who also attended the meeting but wanted to remain anonymous, the motto “we want freedom”.
Further elections are planned for 2019 in Indonesia, but the Papuans say they will not elect Jokowi.
“Jokowi is a man who has good intentions but is surrounded by people associated with the shooting in Paniai,” said Gobau, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai – in addition to living in constant fear of a robbing army – are rolling in poverty, miserable education and the health system.
Gobai claims that the inhabitants of Paniai, like the other Papuans, regard their vote as a "debt" to be paid back to Jokow.
“They don’t want money, they want justice,” he added.
Despite the threats and intimidation of the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting, the last symbolic act of defiance continues: they bury the bodies of the victims on the ground opposite the police and army station.
Knowing that justice will never be done enough, at least it will not allow those responsible to forget their crimes.
"A member of our family was killed," Yacobus said with his head bowed.
"What can we do?"
