EPA chief Scott Pruitt postpones planned directives to reduce Obama administration’s emissions
After the Environmental Protection Agency was sued by fifteen states, its chief Scott Pruitt revoked his earlier decision to postpone the implementation of the former Obama administration’s plan to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
Pruitt introduced the changes in his plan, responding more quickly than previous governments to the needs of state environmental regulators.
However, he did not mention the legal challenge brought against his previous position in the Federal Court of Appeal.
This refers to the last date set for 1 October, when countries should begin to comply with the 2015 regulation to reduce ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would delay the deal by one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid “interference with local decisions or threatening economic growth.”
Pruitt, who held the position of Oklahoma’s Attorney General before taking over as EPA chief by President Donald Trump, has long served as a reliable opponent of more stringent environmental regulations.
Since settling in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved or postponed the regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil industry.
Wednesday’s sudden turnaround is the biggest legal failure for Pruitt’s regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that an EPA executive exceeded its authority in an effort to delay the Obama administration’s plan, which required oil and gas companies to reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday evening, Pruitt proposed his version of ozone standards and strengthened the EPA’s commitment to working with states through complex processes and meeting new standards within a given timeframe.
“During the previous administration, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines and waited for it to be prosecuted by activist groups and others, agreeing to settlement and further scheduling,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits with the EPA in his previous position.
“We don’t believe in regulation through litigation and we take deadlines seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes from it.”
However, the EPA’s statement states that Pruitt may at some point use “the option of delay and all other legally available authorities” to ensure that regulations “will be based on sound policies and the most available information.”
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader overhaul of the ozone rules.
The White House budget approved last month aims to postpone the implementation of the 2015 rules for at least eight years.
The measure was still not passed by the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who headed a coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group would not allow legal pressure.
“Turning the EPA’s views – following our judicial review – is an important victory for the health and safety of the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans who are directly affected by air pollution,” Schneiderman said.
New York was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington, and Washington, D.C.
Ground-level ozone occurs when common harmful substances emitted by cars, power plants, oil refineries, chemical power plants and other sources react in an atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems in sensitive people and thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists welcome Pruitt’s sudden change with gratitude.
“It’s worrying how much pressure we need to develop to change the mindset of those responsible and protect the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to fight the ideological pull of the Trump administration, which is trying to help polluters and special interests.”
