China is lacking tourists.
Beijing is losing billions of dollars due to its visa policy.
China has been trying for decades to exert its influence without the use of force.
It will spend $10 billion a year to support language schools and build universities abroad, push its entertainment industry to foreign markets, and try to attract Western tourists.
Beijing is not doing that.
The state media are talking about a plan to make tourism the driving force of economic transformation and modernization.
However, the number of arrivals increased by only 3.8 percent last year, and about 80 percent of tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
This is due, among other things, to the fact that despite all of its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, assessing the situation in the world’s most populous country Professor of Economics from the University of Beijing Christopher Balding in an article for the Bloomberg agency.
An example that speaks for everything is the Chinese visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free contact with China, the citizens of the other countries must obtain a visa in advance.
The Chinese authorities in the U.S. are therefore crowds comparable to the celebrations of the Chinese New Year.
The visa costs $140, but if you don’t want to wait in line for long hours, you have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such constraints create significant economic barriers.
A study in the Journal of Economics and Finance showed that the need for a visa reduces the number of visitors to a country by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China's gross domestic product and lives there less than one percent of the total population, was visited by 1.8 million Americans.
China often exacerbates this problem itself when tourism uses it to achieve its political goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China restricted shipments to South Korea in the spring as part of a crackdown around the South Korean missile system, the South Koreans retaliated and China avoided it.
In May, the number of visits fell by 42 percent year-on-year, while Japan saw an 85 percent increase.
All this affects macroeconomic stability.
According to a recently published report by the US central bank, China could leave as much as $190 billion as a result of Chinese foreign travel, while China will earn about $35 billion a year as part of the currency sales to incoming tourists.
According to official figures on the development of the balance of payments, China had a deficit of $217 billion in tourism last year, which is equal to 44 percent of China's total surplus in trade in goods.
Thus, a small number of tourists to the country, which is anxiously preventing the outflow of capital, is laying a very painful wound.
However, the above-mentioned factors are only one manifestation of more general restraint towards foreigners.
In many places in China, virtually no one has heard of immigrants.
In 2013, there were less than one million foreigners living in China.
There are more of them in the United States and some individual cities.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroads of immigration, has doubled.
A number of scientific papers show that immigrants usually revive economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.
You will not find them in China.
Solving these problems will be politically challenging, but the step that is offered is to simplify the visa apparatus.
Other Asian countries, notably India and Vietnam, have recently made great efforts to simplify and reduce visa procedures.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currencies, it should be easier for them to get there.
