Since 2005, a group of activists have regularly returned to the Moore's Ford Bridge to reconstruct the fateful night of 1946, when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murra Dorsey - were killed by members of the Kukluxklan.
No one has yet been tried for murder.
"It's surprising that not a single person has been arrested in all these years - even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identities," Tyrone Brooks, who helps organize the reconstruction, said in a statement.
“It is a stain on our history and a burden on our souls.”
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia congressman and lifelong civil rights activist.
In his eyes, the reconstruction of the event is a dramatic call to action, reminding the Monroe community every year that justice has not been done enough.
"We demand prosecution and the closure of the case, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but justice above all," Brooks said.
“Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot begin.”
On July 27, 1946, the coroner covered one of the bodies of the victims of the lynching at Moore's Ford.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were expected to participate in the lynch mob.
However, no one has yet been prosecuted.
Despite the fact that the suspects have been at liberty for decades, civil rights advocates claim that both the reasons for lynchpins – politics and sex – were known to all residents of the city.
In April 1946, on the basis of the Supreme Court’s ruling, blacks in the state of Georgia were granted the right to participate in the elections, which were scheduled for the summer.
And it was during the summer election season, according to the FBI, a black-skinned farmer, Roger Malcolm, was stabbed by a white-skinned landowner, Barnett Hester, during a fight — allegedly for his wife.
According to Brooks, in the city, it was rumored that Hester was hanging out with Malcolm's wife, Dorothy, and brought her into a different state.
On July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, then a prominent landowner, filed a $600 bail for Malcom.
Dorothy and her cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey accompanied him to the prison.
On their return from prison, just before entering Moore's Ford Bridge, a group of suspects paved their way.
"As it turns out, Harrison planned and organized the murders," the FBI said.
“It is also clear that there was a secret agreement between state and local law enforcement officers who not only participated in the lynchpin, but also got rid of the evidence and denied the identity of the witnesses.”
Brooks spoke briefly about the whole thing.
“It was a massacre for the right to vote,” he said.
"The murders had a clear backdrop for all black locals: 'This is how you'll end up if you register and go to vote.'"
The annual reconstruction of the event at Moore's Ford Bridge is organized by Cassandra Greene for almost a decade.
Its performance is figurative, appealing and accurate, showing a deeply rooted racism that many would like to consider extinct in modern America.
Watching this reconstruction isn't easy, and it's even harder to turn a blind eye, but Greene says it makes sense.
“No one wants to talk about lynching because we have to face the unpleasant feelings that are hiding in each of us,” Greene said.
“But there can be no relationship between us if you don’t listen to what I’ve been through.”
The main rehearsals for this year’s reconstruction began in June, and on the first day, about 30 actors – a dozen whites, the rest of the blacks – entered the room, where Greene introduced them to a very carefully planned performance.
Wade Marbaugh is an assistant director.
For many years he played the leader of the Kukluxklan, but according to him the role is exhausting.
"I feel bad about it because it's contrary to who I am," Marbaugh said.
“I think it’s very important to remember this part of history regularly, because we never want to go back to that time.”
Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play the role of Roger Malcom, then Barnett Hester, are exercising their roles.
The show starts with a fight - Malcolm argues with Hester and blames him for having slept with his wife.
"Get out of my land n---e!"
Rascona won't give up.
There's a fight.
At that moment, everyone (at least every black actor) explodes in laughter.
Greene laughs the most.
"What happened?" asked Rascona.
He's confused.
Was I too rude?
"No," said Greene cheerfully.
"I just don't think the whites said 'n--r' in that tone back then."
"Exactly," said one of the black-skinned actors.
"You have to put more emphasis on R."
The energy in the room is suddenly better; enmity will replace the feeling of closeness.
Everyone wants the show to be authentic, just to make it happen with enough of the four victims of the massacre.
The actors repeat the scene.
This time Rascona emphasizes the correct pronunciation of the word in N.
No one's laughing now.
The show ends violently and quickly.
Screams, shots... and silence.
A woman dressed in black stands over the actors’ bodies and sings Billie Holiday’s sad song “Strange Fruit”.
With every word there is sadness in the room.
In the background of all this, about a dozen spectators wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
There is almost the same number of blacks and whites in the audience.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York, and many of the spectators were from nearby towns.
Each of them endures a local humid climate for almost eight hours, and Brooks leads them in crowds to the tombs of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Until now, the murders could have been viewed at a distance, but now, standing in the same place where the lynchpins took place, the atmosphere is spooky.
With the last words of the song, Greene will challenge the crowd to inspect the bodies.
Children kneel to the victims' heads, watch fake blood and immobile bodies, and whisper something in their ears.
"They're not dead," the little boy whispered.
It'll be a few minutes, and Greene will thank the audience.
The actors clean the rope and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw embraces Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the leader of the Kukluxklan.
Nick Rascona embraces his two actor-friends and weeps in their arms; in the end, he is overwhelmed by emotions.
"It's all right," whispered one of the women.
“We know you’re playing that role.
But you had a reason for that."
Later that day, the audience meets with the actors for dinner.
At one table, a young white couple talks passionately about a performance with a black couple they met today.
Denise Duplinski could hardly find words to express her feelings from today’s performance.
“It’s hard to listen to those ugly words and look at those ugly deeds... people who look like you and do it because they look like you,” she said.
“It makes me realize that lynching is still a topical issue,” she added, “it’s just called police brawls.”
On the other side of the room, Tyrone Brooks sits in the courtroom, enjoying dinner and talking about civil rights.
According to his own words, he has already started planning a performance for the next year.
“The reconstruction of these events is inspiring as it describes the fear we had to experience – but it’s also a moment to think about,” he said.
“If we don’t learn from it, who knows... it could happen again.
People who do not know and study the history of their country are doomed to repeat it.”
