NHS to Prescribe Controversial HIV Drug to 10,000 Patients
Patients will gain access to ‘transformative’ HIV prevention treatment starting in September following the Supreme Court’s decision on funding the NHS drug.
The National Health Service (NSH) has announced that a pre-exposure prophylaxis pill (PrEP), which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through a health service to approximately 10,000 patients as part of a three-year trial.
NSH agreed to fund the probation period after the appeals court backed last year’s Supreme Court ruling, stating that the NHS has the funds to pay for PrEP despite a statement that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, which was announced on Thursday, was accepted by NHS England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a “significant intervention,” while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a “decisive moment.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients. Further clinics will join in October and will be fully implemented across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medicine given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission between at-risk patients.
The application of PrEP before sex means that there is a sufficient amount of specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not being treated successfully.
The clinics will identify eligible participants who sign consent to participate in the testing, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status has not yet been controlled by the appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with the GP in the UK can also apply at their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will come to taxpayers at <0xC2><0xA3>10 million and NHS England signed a drug distribution contract this week after obtaining an international public procurement.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: ‘This important intervention should complement and fully leverage the ever-expanding and increasingly successful HIV prevention effort.
It’s another milestone in more than 30 years of trying to stop one of the biggest challenges to human health.”
Deborah Gold, executive director of the National Aids Trust (NAT), said: “We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and patients at risk, it will offer the possibility of transforming the English HIV epidemic.
Since September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will lead to the improvement of the quality of many lives.
We welcome this statement with pleasure.'
Ian Green, CEO of Terrence Higgins Trust, said: ‘Priority number one must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure that it is available to every patient.
We now have a trial PrEP drug at our disposal and are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.”
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “The beginning of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will lead us one step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
“It is now important that we start testing as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are exposed to HIV and together to stop the spread of HIV in society.”
