The murder of a journalist highlights the growing threats in Mexico
Employees of Riodoce meet regularly every Wednesday to discuss the news of the riots that are taking place in the Sinaloa area with the participation of organized criminals, corrupt officials and relentless drug wars.
Today, however, they are meeting under the pressure of recent events mainly for their own safety.
They learn that it is important to change their habits.
Two well-deserved journalists talk about what would be safer: taking their children with them to an office that was attacked by a grenade in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts have written three simple words on the blackboard: opponents, neutrals and allies.
They ask journalists to give names to every word - no evidence is needed, just use imagination and foresight.
Picking them out of what - drug dealers, politicians, traders and journalists are suspected of taking money from the government or drug cartels - is a catalog of criminals whose task is to cover up criminal acts.
Violence does not stop and bodies are piled up across the country; journalists among them are constantly growing: according to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists, at least 25 of them have been under federal protection since President Enrique Pena Nieto came to power in December 2012; 589 journalists have been under federal protection and are under threat after the attacks.
Among them is the co-founder of Riodioce, editor and inspiration for colleagues, Javier Valdez Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and work as a journalist,” Valdez wrote in one of his many books on the violence associated with the drug trade.
His loss is palpable, even though his presence is omnipresent - a large photograph of Valdez with the inscription "Justice", to which the middleman points, hangs in the front of the building; two journalists - Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez - over 30 years old, have a t-shirt with a photo of Valdez on the nose with a smile on the face.
The meeting takes place less than two months after his death; journalists talk about mutual trauma, nightmares, insomnia and paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor’s office was set up in 2010 to deal with journalists’ cases, two suspects have been prosecuted so far, according to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists.
Most of the thousands of murders that occur every year are linked to drug trafficking and organized crime, so journalist killers are very exceptionally brought to justice.
Journalists from Riodoce insist that they will report on the violence that is taking place in Sinaloa; despite the fact that they are devastated by grief and the said territory is currently very treacherous.
Without information about the murders and without a view of justice, the security meeting is pointless, Ibarra says.
"It's foolish to waste time on such meetings," he adds.
"Unless we get more information, you can't trust anyone."
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left Riodoce headquarters in Culiacán, the capital of Sinaloa.
He managed to escape several blocks when his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men who pulled him out of the car and killed him with 12 bullets, apparently because of the title of the article - which can be translated as the Twelfth River.
The shooters then stepped into his car and assaulted him not far from the crime scene.
Valdez died at the age of 50.
He left behind a wife and two adult children.
In Culiacan, rumours seem to be spreading rapidly.
In Valdez’s case, however, there is only suspicious silence.
Since Guzmán’s arrest last year and his January extradition to the United States, Sinaloa has become one of the country’s bloodiest battlefields as rival factions try to fill the void.
Every day, several people are killed in the streets of Sinaloa and the cemeteries are filled with jeweled two-storey mausoleums for drug kings, many of which are larger than houses.
Forget for a moment that the word “ceasefire” means that one drug cartel controls a coastal state with precious ports and important routes that drug travels to the United States.
Despite this, as well as the fact that Valdez was intimately acquainted with the risks of his employment, Ismail Bojorquez, 60, co-founder and CEO of Riodoce, still blames him for failing to protect his friend.
He believes that two mistakes contributed to his death.
The first was the February issue of an interview with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival drug cartels that waged war with the sons of Joaquín Guzmán.
The peace might have pissed off the sons; the suspected gang members bought all copies of the newspaper as they landed on the counters.
The second mistake was not to force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after seizing other newspapers in which the same story was printed.
Valdez has become a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his death is seen as an important milestone in the fight of Mexican criminals against journalists.
He managed to survive for so long and all his friends and colleagues believed that it would never change.
In the magazine Noroeste, he was practically a veteran when in 2003 he decided to sell his $50 shares and found along with five colleagues Riodoce.
In Sinaloa, “it was impossible to run journalism without mentioning the drug trade,” Bojorquez said.
Riodoce eventually gained a good reputation for brave and truthful news; the newspapers began to thrive.
The journalists liked to search for problematic topics and publish texts without censorship - the readers were fascinated by stories that no one else dared to publish.
Eight years after its founding, Riodoce won the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Award for reporting on Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee for the Protection of Journalists for his brave reporting on the Mexican drug trade.
Valdez openly admitted that he was afraid.
"I was worried about my life," he said at the awards ceremony.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is a “way of life,” Valdez said in October last year in an interview with Rompeviento TV.
“You have to take on the role of a journalist – or play stupid.
I don’t want anyone to ask me, ‘What did you do in the face of death... why didn’t you tell me what was going on?’”
Riodoce's employees miss Valdez. The man was known for his jokes and non-selective language. He was a good friend who liked to give advice and hugs - a teacher who knew how to survive.
Everyone relied on his day-to-day routine.
He always wore his hat.
He often went to the El Guayabo bar opposite the offices and sat at the same table.
Now they ask: did this routine cause his death?
His death in them also raised questions about his own assumptions - how to do his job as best as possible and stay alive?
“They don’t like it when you mess up with their wives, their children, their clean shops, their secret landing pads.”
"These things were forbidden," Bojorquez said.
As a result, there is a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
If you feel that something is not playing out here, put your hands away.
The problem is, Riodoce editor Andres Villarreal said, “Silence is a sense that can be fooled... and then the thing with Javier happened.”
The old rules, according to him, as well as others, no longer apply in Sinaloa – just as in the states of Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states that are home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling trails, weak governments and corrupt politicians.
The country is constantly changing.
No mobile phones are allowed in the room where Riodoce employees meet, as spyware was discovered a few days ago, which was purchased by governments to monitor Mexican journalists and activists.
In front of the building, two police officers find relief from a forty-degree heat in the shadow of a nearby tree.
They were selected by the state to protect the offices of Riodoce, which are located in a four-storey building in the urban district of Culiacan.
Journalists are wondering if these policemen are among the 50 percent of the law enforcement officers who, according to the government, are corrupt.
It has been several months since journalists last went to the mountainous areas, which are essentially controlled by drug cartels.
There are three main stories on the agenda this week.
The first is the murder of the brother of former boxer Julio César Chávez in Sinaloa.
They are also aware of suspicious government spending that took place in the state's hometown of the governor.
Recently, there have also been several kidnappings in one of Culiacán’s most luxurious restaurants, just a block from the prosecutor’s office.
Officially, no one announced the identities of the abducted people or the circumstances of the kidnapping, so journalists were on guard when they were going to write about what everyone in the city knows: that the restaurant is a favorite destination for drug dealers and politicians.
One journalist read from public records that the restaurant was registered under a name that is associated with a certain politician who is a member of the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), controlling all levels of the political scene for almost the last century.
Several PRI governors have recently been charged with corruption in high-ranking positions.
Villarreal asked reporters to write about earlier incidents that occurred in the restaurant, including an incident in which one of Joaquín "El Chapo" Guzmán's sons escaped an army intervention unit.
A month ago, readers would have read about it in Valdez’s column, which was the best source of information about the kidnappings.
"Valdez would certainly solve the case," said Villarreal, 46, who is nicknamed "El Flaco" for his slim figure.
"Now all the informants have turned their backs on us."
Valdez's office has turned into a warehouse of placards and stickers for protests against the killing of journalists. Employees certainly did not expect them to become activists in the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez grabbed several billboards and went out the next morning to demonstrate in front of the prosecutor’s office for another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared just three days after Valdez’s murder in the western state of Michoacán.
Only a burnt body was found, and authorities say it's Adame based on DNA analysis.
The activity of journalists is increasing all over the country. Many of them organize protests and whistle on the sidewalks and buildings "SOS Press".
Newspaper director Bojorquez is on a day visit to Washington, D.C., where he seeks international support and justice for Valdez’s death.
At a meeting with Governor Sinaloa the day after Valdez’s murder, Ramirez accused authorities of tracking journalists and their murders for telling the truth.
In the meantime, she requested transfer to another department for fear that her anger might jeopardize her impartiality.
Valdez has repeatedly said that Mexican journalists are “overwhelmed” by organized crime, corrupt officials and the indifferent public.
In his latest book, Narco-Journalism, he wrote that journalists are dying not only at the hands of drug cartels, but also at the behest of politicians and security forces who cooperate with organized crime.
The Articulo 19 media watchdog has accused more than half of all attacks on police journalists and public officials.
“You will die in Mexico because they want to silence you,” Ramirez added.
Murders seem to work.
No one will forget the death of the blogger Marie Elizabeth Macías, who died six years ago at the northern border of Tamaulipas.
Her body was found along with a message allegedly signed by the Zetas cartel: “This is how I ended up because of my messages.”
Next to the cut head lay the keyboard and the headphones.
Some branches have decided to close operations, such as the newspaper El Norte, which is based on the northern borders of the state of Chihuahua, in response to the March murder of reporter Miroslava Breach.
Others are still continuing, just as they did El Manana of Nuevo Laredo after killing its director in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juarez publicly addressed drug cartels with an article on the front page titled “What do you want from us”?
Some journalists have fled their homes or even across the border.
It's a difficult decision.
Finding a job in exile is difficult, as well as getting rid of the feeling that someone is constantly harassing you.
And journalists are being persecuted and killed, such as in the case of Ruben Espinosa, who was murdered in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico City, three months after fleeing from Veracruz.
For those who choose to stay and not give up their work, every day presents a great risk.
Ibarra, who once wanted to be a poet, admits that writing about drugs scares him.
“Mexico is going to hell, that’s why I became a journalist,” he said.
