Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, however scary.
Researchers have now uncovered the first findings of an amazing rhino-sized creature whose perfectly preserved remains — which experts have dubbed the Mona Lisa of Dinosaurs — have been found by a Canadian miner.
The remains have been preserved to such an extent that experts have been able to determine the reddish-brown color of its scaly skin, saying the dinosaur had a "problem past."
An article in the journal Current Biology said it was “the most preserved armoured dinosaur ever found and one of the best dinosaur species in the world.”
The fossil is a new species of the family Nodosauridae. Dinosaur lived in the Cretaceous period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
His perfectly preserved condition literally shocked the researchers, who described it with the words “really remarkable.”
According to National Geographic, the armored biologist is the best-preserved fossil of its kind.
The discovery was made by Shawn Funk, who discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling in the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
He stumbled upon something that looked like a foreign object and decided to examine it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The researchers spent the next six years uncovering an animal from a huge piece of land weighing 1,100 kg.
After the work is completed, the dinosaur is ready for detection.
“You just have to blink a little and you’ll believe that he’s sleeping,” said Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is on display.
“It will certainly be recorded in history as one of the most beautiful and most well-preserved species of dinosaurs – the Mona Lisa dinosaurs.”
In a study of his skin, researchers found that this herbivore — despite being covered in armor and reminiscent of a walking tank — was most likely facing a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a masking system used by many animals today.
Experts claim that this allowed him to better merge with his surroundings and avoid enemies. The masking system suggests that he was a favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
Reports of a 110-million-year-old Nodosauridae dinosaur first appeared in the papers in May. Currently available for viewing at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who spent more than 7,000 hours with the team carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the amazingly preserved state of the fossil, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the patterns and shape of scales and armor throughout the body.
They discovered a method of masking commonly used by today's animals in defense - the upper part of the animal was darker than its lower part.
Although this masking effect is common in nature, the researchers’ findings are surprising, as Borealopelta’s size far exceeds today’s animals using the same technique.
