A Becoming Similarity: Artist Makes Portraits Using Chelsea Manning’s DNA
In the middle of one of the rooms of the New York Fridman Gallery are several faces of different shades of skin - white, black and brown - suspended from the ceiling on the wires, each of them as if out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by the artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from wipes made of oral cavity and hair sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized disclosure of secret cables on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which was launched on August 2, is titled A Becoming Similarity.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience in technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transgender and pioneer dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before she stepped down as president of the United States.
Using an algorithmic analysis of Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to depict what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a sharp, if not intellectual commentary on the susceptibility of DNA - as well as on the many ways that DNA can be interpreted in the same way - and the indistinguishable identities.
Manning, born Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken out about being considered a woman since she was a teenager and was convicted in 2013 on twenty charges, including violation of six espionage laws, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photographs were held by prison staff, and only one black and white lower-quality photograph escaped the public, on which Manning, visibly worried, sits in the driver’s seat in a platinum blonde wig, with which she is now attached.
In 2015, they were still receiving positive reactions to the 2012 Stranger Visions project by Dewey-Hagborg.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic subjects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create an image of possible images of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were planning an interview with Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to add a portrait to the article," Dewey-Hagborg said.
However, visits and photography were not allowed, so they asked Chelsea if she would be interested in DNA portraits.
The artist and her imprisoned muse were scammed over the course of two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were favored and could attend the exhibition in person.
In fact, a few days after the release of the comic, President Obama asked for Manning’s release, which was a welcome change after several unbearable years spent in a Kansas military prison.
It’s really interesting that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging war with people seeking to release government information and transgender soldiers while trying to find new ways to incite resentment in areas he’s supposed to support with his tweets.
In response to a question about this particular timing, Dewey-Hagborg said that “everything is happening for some reason.”
Under the artist's statement on one of the gallery's walls, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter "i" in the surname is pronounced with a heart) after the end of "self-made factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture."
On the opposite side are the sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - the centipedes of the letters C, G and A recorded by the pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist’s sophisticated scientific dictionary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
“I hope that people will learn that our genome doesn’t care who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way,” said Dewey-Hagborg, who is also featured in her 2007 work on video, Spurious Memories.
“DNA tells a lot of different stories, these are 30 of them.”
The last copy of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is the only page of the above-mentioned graphic novel.
It shows Manning emerging in the manner of King Kong from the United States Disciplinary Barracks with a megaphone in his hand.
“As soon as they stop you from speaking, they will win,” it says.
“Never let yourself be silenced.”
"It's a direct transcript of one of the letters," the Philadelphia artist said.
"When I think about it, my goose's skin bounces."
Manning has not yet personally visited the exhibition - as predicted in the comic book - but when it does, she will be greeted in the middle of the room with her masks, her own genome images, arranged like a crowd of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including a nearly 160 cm tall statue of Maning on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded with a pencil.
“In the past, they were placed on the walls, but this time I wanted them to feel crowded,” Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
“I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes on the form of Chelsea and liberates it.”
