Startups That Will Help Your Company Not Become Another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the level of employee satisfaction of her e-commerce startup, but did not find the appropriate survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even misleading.
And despite promising anonymity to the survey, some employees expressed their mistrust of the entire process.
“I was looking for consistency and objectivity,” said Errett, owner of the San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
He asked for help from outside.
New HR startups are constantly appearing on the market, helping companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific purpose of measuring employee obligations, startups allow companies to conduct rapid voting, target specific teams and demographic groups, and offer complete anonymity to employees and a hotline for contacting the complainants and informing them.
“There are tools like Strava and Fitbit on the market that monitor your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said Glint made her more aware of what her employees were thinking and feeling in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and voting of specific teams, Glint offers a company temperature map and a seamless overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of managers with low ratings - allowing the user to work on the fix.
Companies are beginning to realize that it is necessary to take care of the culture of the work environment - in case they become another Uber - which is messed up in scandals after a former employee posted on his blog a post describing the corporate environment and harassment of employees who are open to taking action.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let’s Talk Payments website, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado-based Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year, just before the Uber scandal.
Among Convercent’s nearly 600 clients are Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has also taken over its wings.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable “flash” surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved in the problem, the complaints are sent directly to the Board of Directors.
“The court of public opinion has authorized regulators,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
If a company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or unethical behavior – and if regulators do not intervene – it may face costly consequences as a result of customer boycotts, employee exhaustion or court proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for over a year to raise employee awareness of corporate policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate management.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to search for a phone number or e-mail to the management of the company, formally file a complaint and hope for a sound solution.
It was often a frightening and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday’s chief executive, who said there had previously been no reliable way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company uses Convercent, it ensures quick detection and resolution of problems that have never before reached managers sitting in offices miles away from real complaints – such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
“It’s closer to a holistic, overall view of employee experience,” said Vitrano, who heads Ruby Tuesday’s risk management group.
“We also protect shareholders from legal disputes on the part of employees.”
The companies stopped taking employee ethics, values, and participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after Enron’s collapse over employee ethical rights abuses, Quinlan said.
But it wasn’t until “you lit up the whole thing on social media” that companies began to realize that in the online world they couldn’t just hide their bones in the closet.
“Before people started using technology to track ethics, they relied on faith,” Quinlan added.
Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which the company pays regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity endorsed by bold capital investors who have supported both startups.
As part of its February campaign, Convercent selected a total of $10 million from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and eventually took out capital of $47 million.
Glint earned $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and earned $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the reciprocal nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing number of surveys clearly confirms that today’s employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are not the main advantage.
Employees want to see that they are accepted and appreciated and that they devote their time to a company that strives for a positive mission.
“If people are happy in their work, they feel that their voice is heard and that their work is rewarding, they strive for the success of the company,” said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee benefits at LinkedIn, which uses Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money if companies prosper and companies thrive if their employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool emerges in the market that ensures employee engagement and commitment to the company, it’s no wonder that there are a lot of investors who will support this effort.
According to experts on working culture, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is useless unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The fact is that once the company requests feedback from its employees, there can be big changes.
And if the change does not happen quickly - in the worst case of all - it can cause frustration and disinterest of employees.
“Once you ask for 4,000 opinions, you have to be ready for 4,000 conversations,” said Russell Raath, chief consulting officer at Kotter International, who witnessed many companies relying too much on the data itself.
“Because as soon as you don’t get things done, employees begin to ask themselves, ‘Did they hear me at all?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, why should I care?'"
Madison Reed, who now conducts monthly employee surveys on a regular basis, will be able to solve the problem in one day thanks to Glint, Errett said.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated by slow decision making and quality of communication, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and start training communication to successfully solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important view of its employees and hopes that in the long term it will achieve high employment in an industry that is known for frequent redundancies.
“Unless you strive to create a transparent work environment, employees won’t believe you,” Vitrano added.
“And once you start losing employees, you lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company collapses.”
