Creating a Graphic Novel: The Story of A Castle in England
The small Scotney Castle recently starred in the Squeeze music video, and Margaret Thatcher also took refuge in it during the 1970s and 1980s.
Scotney, however, has witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his cozy spot on the Bewl River in British Kent, which inspired the curly Jamie Rhodes of York County – known for his love of historical documents – to create a graphic novel.
“The look at the font of a man who is 300 years after death fascinates me,” Rhodes says with a serious face.
“When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection.”
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who lived in Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, this is not Rhodes' first archive-inspired book: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by the British Library documents - a project that was very emotional for him.
“I got a fingerprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jacobites,” he said.
“That’s his fingerprint.
And the letters always smell like smoke, because in those times you had to light a candle to read.
If I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm back in time.
I love the archives!”
For someone so fascinated by the old papers, the support from the National Trust and the Arts Council England is the ability to spend nearly four months in the castle almost like a dream.
Rhodes spent his time exploring the Victorian “new” castle, browsing the archives and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of the hyena on the wall and bottles that had been thrown in the trench for centuries.
He strolled through the plot and explored the ruins of the old castle, talking to hogs, gardeners and sometimes also to artists who worked on illustrations of his book.
In the night, he drank whiskey and wrote.
Scotney's confidential history is relatively large, as the National Trust did not gain access to the documents until after the death of her last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the employees were only beginning to penetrate the archives that Rhodes described in words, as when "aristocrats of many centuries threw their hands with the words: 'Take it to the attic.'"
Journals, letters from the times of the British Empire, maps depicting property: “You may think the land dispute is boring,” said Rhodes, “but I came across one case where two families were dragging on birch.
Leave it, people!"
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a bridge of reflection and dive deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English Uprising of 1381.
“I found a record of a 1380 castle uprising that was called the Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex in the book,” Rhodes said.
“The English uprising actually started in this area and I thought the uprising was a good starting point.
They may eventually have something to do with each other.”
Other stories are closely linked to the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who had been hiding from Darrell's family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was discovered only a few years after the coffin was discovered).
Darrell's favorite family is Rhodes: "I was taken over by the male generation - the men of that time were always indebted and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Different generations of the Darrells dealt with it by marrying rich or old ladies – I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who loved to mow their heads to the heirs.
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes is looking for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week hike in the Finnish wilderness, where he drew inspiration for his next book on Eleämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was engulfed by nature.
This is a special place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
"I thought to myself, 'Now to get back to real life.'"
