Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can alleviate the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
However, a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million U.S. residents and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to eat meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms, but researchers at Washington University have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to create immune cells that support intestinal resistance.
Dr. Marco Colonna, the lead author of the study, explained that immune cells protect the gut and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging the sensitive tissue.
Once the bowls of the scales are inclined to the side of the inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, the researchers found the presence of immune cells supporting the tolerance of the body in the stomach of mice with a specific bacterium.
This bacteria requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to form cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have found a link between one type of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is a common component of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that support the body’s tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more immune cells they had.”
At the same time, he suggested that if it turns out that the same applies to humans, then the combination of L. reuteri and tryptophan-rich diets would help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
Postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, in a study of a certain type of immune cells supporting body tolerance, found that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice kept separately lacked cells.
It was derived from the fact that one group of mice has a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that commonly reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of mice were tested by DNA sorting, and the researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that were missing from the second group of mice.
The mice, which were kept in a sterile environment and lacked a gut microbiome - so they did not develop this type of immune cells - were given L. reuteri bacteria - and created immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria affects the immune system, the researchers cultivated L. reuteri in fluid and then transferred small amounts of fluid - without the bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells that were stored in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removal of the active ingredient from the liquid, it was found to be a by-product of a tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. After splitting doses of tryptophan at the same time, the number of cells decreased by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us keep L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: “Each of us should probably strive for the development of these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can increase cell populations."
