White House Requisition Costs Taxpayers Thousands of Dollars
The White House’s decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the U.S. manufacturing industry, which took place last month, came to $24,000, according to Navy records published by TIME Weekly.
The green-white helicopter Sikorsky VH-3D, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the culmination of the July 17 White House program, which was a parade of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials watched a show of products from all 50 states.
A helicopter from Connecticut was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a forklift truck from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order or FRAGO and requested the helicopter to be present less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn as part of an "extraordinary" event, Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) records said.
"I wanted to make sure that you were aware of such a significant event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the deputy commander of the navy for the aviation the day before the event began.
The report suggested that the helicopter will arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 a.m. on the occasion of the parade, which is scheduled to begin at 3 p.m. and will remain in place until the entire site is completely cleared, which was scheduled between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m.
The email also stated that if there is a delay in departure from the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for the return flight due to the working time regulations.
The original crew remained on the scene that evening, along with the helicopter and the security guards.
From the records - obtained by TIME - it was not clear whether the second crew was eventually dispatched.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government property for political purposes.
The records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible breach of this Regulation.
“We were wondering if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was okay,” the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you're being blocked," the deputy commander replied.
This show "Made in America" was designated by the White House as an official event and the Hatch Act would therefore not apply to it.
But the official events also have political subtexts.
In his participation in the event, the president advocated health reform, which passed through the Senate, and talked about efforts to keep government regulations in check.
The use of aviation vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when traveling.
However, their presence for purely presentational reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane drove in the background at his first meeting as part of the campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’ show, which features products from all 50 states that Americans make from American materials,” said Lindsay Walters, a spokeswoman for the White House.
Crews of HMX-1 helicopters often train landings in the Washington area and on the South Lawn and train possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 exercise landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America parade was part of the current crew training, the state official said.
The helicopter's unit flew on the same day as part of "non-presidential support missions" for another eleven hours.
The White House said no additional props were paid from taxpayers’ money.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was in no way interested in negotiating the helicopter’s exposure to South Lawn.
The HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the parade is difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Ministry of Defense, the hourly price for fiscal year 2017, the refund of DoD expenses for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records a time of 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of helicopters are well below this amount.
“It is very misleading to state taxpayers’ costs on the basis of estimates for reimbursement of expenses,” Walters said.
“These estimates include personnel, maintenance, and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual costs.”
According to the 2015 RAND study, the reimbursement of DoD expenses does not include the cost of personnel, but includes the cost of fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the purpose of the parade.
“The idea of the show taking place this week is to introduce products made in the United States,” Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud to contribute to the defense of our state, and that they provide jobs for hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other military facilities that countless American citizens are involved in producing.
This fact should be remembered."
It is not clear whether Trump was also looking at the helicopter during his tour of South Lawn. With certainty, it can only be said that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back in the White House, Trump spoke to a representative of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the President, "I own three of them."
