GMB chief organizer Drew Duffy added: “The fact that we have not received a clear response from the builder regarding the needs of the company and the future investment plan in Tollcross is very worrying for our members.
Generations of many families have worked here, and employees come mostly from the local community and the Glasgow area, where work at the factory here is a critical pillar of decent employment in the area of high unemployment and social exclusion.
In terms of work, wages and profitability – and despite the prospect of Brexit, rising costs of living and falling production – the eastern part of Glasgow needs a desperately prosperous manufacturer like McVitie’s.”
A spokesperson for Pladis said: “Builder Tollcross received a letter from GMB yesterday and the company will issue a statement as soon as possible as we appreciate the continued commitment to employees and trade union representatives.
A regular meeting with employees and representatives of GMB in Tollcross took place two months ago and many issues were openly discussed at this meeting.
We have told our employees that, as in all companies operating in extremely competitive and uncertain economic conditions, we evaluate our operations on a regular basis, which applies to all our operations, so that we can continue to successfully compete with others.
She added: “In recent years, we have invested <0xC2><0xA3>5 million in Tollcross, especially in production lines and operational efficiency.
We value the heritage of Tollcross and the locality very much and in the event of any changes in the operation of the factory here, employees and representatives of the trade unions will be informed immediately."
